This completes the proof of the theorem. Therefore, we have shown that for all $n > 1$, $n! > e \cdot \left(\frac{n}{e}\right)^n$.

The key insight is that the factorial function grows faster than any exponential function in the long run, as measured by the ratio $n!/e \cdot (n/e)^n$. This is a direct consequence of the fact that $n!$ is the product of $n$ terms, each of which is greater than or equal to $1$, and for large $n$, the product of these terms will dominate any exponential expression.
